<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="68" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="68">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="68">
(After 
<bibRefCitation author="Barber, HG" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Americana" pageId="20" pageNumber="71" pagination="149 - 238" title="Essay on the subfamily Stenopodinae of the New World." volume="10" year="1930">Barber 1930</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Giacchi, JC" journalOrPublisher="Physis" pageId="21" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 26" title="Revision del genero Stenopoda Laporte, 1833 (Hemiptera, Reduviidae, Stenopodainae)." volume="29" year="1969">Giacchi 1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Giacchi, JC" journalOrPublisher="Physis" pageId="21" pageNumber="72" pagination="47 - 59" title="Revision de los Stenopodainos Americanos. IX. El genero Stenopoda Laporte, 1833 (Heteroptera, Reduviidae). Enmiendas y notas adicionales." volume="46" year="1988 b">Giacchi 1988b</bibRefCitation>
) First labial segment shorter than the second and third segments combined. Postocular region shorter than preocular one. Body and appendages with dense, adpressed pubescence and numerous tiny, erect bristles. Margins of head nearly parallel-sided in dorsal view, abruptly constricted at neck. Two median dorsal carinae (1+1) more or less elevated.
</paragraph>
